'''James Philip Milner''' (born [[January 4]] [[1986]], [[Wortley, West Yorkshire|Wortley]], [[West Yorkshire]]) is an [[English people|English]] [[footballer]] who plays as a [[winger (sport)|winger]] and left-sided [[midfielder]] for the English club [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]. 

As a child, Milner was recognised as a talent in football, [[cricket]] and [[long-distance track event|long distance running]]. He represented his school in each, and also played football for teams from [[Rawdon, West Yorkshire|Rawdon]] and [[Horsforth]]. He supported [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] from a young age and was a [[season ticket]] holder at the club before becoming a ball boy.

Milner began his career at Leeds United, joining the Leeds United academy. He was later taken on as a trainee, and made his first appearance for the first team in 2002, aged only 16. He achieved prominence by becoming the youngest player ever to score in the [[Premier League]], aged 16 years and 309 days. 

While at Leeds United, he spent some time on loan to [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] to gain first team experience. Following his move to Newcastle United, he was loaned to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] during the 2005–06 season. He has since established himself in the Newcastle first team and has now made over a hundred appearances for them. He creates scoring chances and  does not score many goals. Outside of football he is an easygoing person who rarely speaks to the media. At international level, he has made a record number of appearances for the [[England U21 national football team|England Under-21]] side. He remains part of the Newcastle starting eleven, featuring regularly in domestic and European games.
==Early life==
Born in [[Wortley, West Yorkshire|Wortley]], and raised in [[Horsforth]], [[Leeds]], Milner played most of his football as a child for Westbrook School in Horsforth. While playing there, Graeme Coulson, a coach from [[Rawdon, West Yorkshire|Rawdon]], recognised his talent and asked who he was. Coulson persuaded Milner to play for his Rawdon side in various tournaments, and the team went on to win a "prestigious" tournament in Rawdon Meadows with Milner scoring four goals in the final.<ref name="Milner child"/>
