Milner was described as a "first class" student at Westbrook School, and left with 11 [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSEs]], as well as an award for his performance in [[physical education]].<ref name="Milner child"/><ref name="Sunday Telegraph">{{cite web
| last = Collins
| first = Roy
|url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?xml=/sport/2007/09/09/sfnmil109.xml 
|title = James Milner keeps feet on the ground  
|publisher= Sunday telegraph 
|date = [[2007-09-09]]
|accessdate = 2007-09-09}}</ref> Milner supported [[Leeds United]] from a very young age — he and his parents Peter and Lesley were all Leeds United [[season ticket]] holders, and Milner even became a [[ball boy]] because he wanted to get closer to the action. His earliest memory of Leeds is watching them win the [[FA Youth Cup]] in 1993.<ref name="findarticles">{{cite web
  | last = Shaw
  | first = Phil
|url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20051231/ai_n15981206 
|title = FOOTBALL THE PREMIERSHIP INTERVIEW: One to watch in 2006: 'Players 
|publisher=findarticles 
|date = [[2005-12-31]]
|accessdate = 2007-07-28}}</ref> He also showed talent in [[cricket (sport)|cricket]] and played for the Yorkshire Schools team, and was an impressive [[Sprint (race)|sprinter]] and [[Cross country running|long distance runner]]. He was the cross-country champion at his school for three consecutive years and the district champion over 100 metres for two years in row.<ref name="Milner child"/>

When Milner was ten he joined the Leeds United Academy after he was spotted by a [[scout (sport)|scout]] while playing for [[Horsforth#Education|Westbrook]] Juniors in Horsforth.<ref name="Milner child"/> However, his father insisted that he attend college once a week to keep up with his education.<ref name="findarticles2">{{cite web
| last = Townsend
| first = Nick
|url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4159/is_20040104/ai_n9690186/pg_1 
|title = Football: The Interview James Milner: The birthday boy in a very 
|publisher=findarticles 
|date = [[2004-01-04]]
|accessdate = 2007-08-13}}</ref> While at the academy, he played against contemporaries from other clubs in the north, including [[Wayne Rooney]]. His role model was Leeds-born striker [[Alan Smith]]. Milner believed the chance to play with Smith worked as a learning curve because he had done what Milner was aspiring to do — to come through the Academy and play for first team.<ref name="findarticles"/> Making good progress at the academy, he was taken on as a trainee after leaving school. He remarked that he had to pinch himself playing alongside first team players such as [[David Batty]] and [[Olivier Dacourt]], but also said he did not want to get excited and think that he "had already made it".<ref name="Sunday Telegraph"/> He continued to improve his skills with the youth team, playing for the [[Republic of Ireland#Sport|Republic of Ireland]] at Under-14 level and England at Under-15 and Under-17 levels.<ref name="Milner child"/><ref>{{cite web
| last = Wrigglesworth
| first = Dave
|url = https://www.horsforth.leeds.sch.uk/newslet/dec00/sports.asp
|title = PROFILE OF JAMES MILNER:  AGED 14 YEARS 
|publisher= Horsforth School website
|accessdate = 2007-09-09}}</ref> He helped England win the 2002 Under-17 Nationwide summer tournament against Italy, Czech Republic and Brazil, with a goal against the latter.<ref name="Under-17">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/U17s/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2002/07 |title=Milner magic seals Nationwide Glory |publisher=[[The FA]] |date=[[2002-07-14]] |accessdate=2007-07-28}}</ref>

==Career==
Milner has played for four major national clubs at senior level: [[Leeds United]], [[Swindon Town]] (on loan from Leeds), [[Newcastle United]] and [[Aston Villa]] (on loan from Newcastle). He has also played for the England Under-21 international side, appearing in over thirty matches. He once held the record for the youngest player ever to score in the [[Premier League]], as well as second youngest player ever to play in the Premier League.
===Leeds United===
[[Image:Th milnerleeds.jpg|left|thumb|200px|Milner with Leeds during the [[2002-03 in English football|2002&ndash;03 season]].]]
Milner's début for [[Leeds United]] came on [[10 November]] [[2002]] when he replaced [[Jason Wilcox]] for the final six minutes in a game against [[West Ham United]]. The appearance made him the second youngest player ever to play in the [[Premier League]], at the age of 16 years and 309 days.<ref name="ESPN"/> On [[Boxing Day]] that year he became the youngest scorer in the history of the Premier League with a goal in a 2&ndash;1 win against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]].<ref>{{cite web
  | title = The Premiership's youngest guns
  | publisher = [[BBC]]
  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sportacademy/hi/sa/football/features/newsid_2609000/2609487.stm
  | accessdate = 2007-08-11 }}</ref> He celebrated both this and his début with a "quiet night in".<ref name="Sunday Telegraph"/> In a later match he scored a goal against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] that impressed many reporters. His first touch was described as "a beauty" and allowed him to avoid a tackle from [[Marcel Desailly]] and create a yard of space to deliver a curling shot from 18&nbsp;yards away.<ref name="Chelsea goal">{{cite web
  | title = Goal of the week - Master Milner's class act 
  | publisher = BBC
  | date = [[2002-12-22]]
  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/2613467.stm
  | accessdate = 2007-09-13 }}</ref> His desire, ability with both feet and confidence in the game impressed several reporters — Milner's performance prompted comparisons to England internationals [[Michael Owen]] and [[Wayne Rooney]], who also came to prominence as teenagers.<ref name="Chelsea">{{cite web
  | last = Lawrence
  | first = Amy
  | title = Magical Milner
  | publisher = [[The Guardian]]
  | date = [[2002-12-28]]
  | url = http://football.guardian.co.uk/Observer_Match_Report/0,,-40980,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-28 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | title = 'Roonaldo', Milner threaten to outdo Owen
  | publisher = Super Soccer
  | date = [[2003-01-03]]
  | url = http://www.supersoccer.co.za/?id=73618&des=article&scat=
  | accessdate = 2007-08-13 }}</ref> The [[BBC]] even asked in a poll if he was a better prospect than Rooney.<ref name="Chelsea goal"> Chelsea manager [[Claudio Ranieri]] said after the game that he had performed like a much more experienced player.<ref name="Chelsea2">{{cite web
  | last = Taylor
  | first = Daniel
  | title = Milner fills Leeds with teen spirit
  | publisher = [[The Guardian]]
  | date = [[2002-12-30]]
  | url = http://football.guardian.co.uk/Match_Report/0,,-40980,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-28 }}</ref>
On [[10 February]] [[2003]], Milner signed a new five-year contract with Leeds after more promising displays.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Milner signs Leeds deal
  | publisher = BBC
  | date = [[2003-02-10]]
  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/leeds_united/2745555.stm
  | accessdate = 2007-08-11 }}</ref>
[[Image:Milnercross.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Milner, (in white, playing for England under-21s) delivers a cross.]]
At the start of the [[2003-04 in English football|2003&ndash;04 season]], Milner was sent on a month-long loan to [[Football League One|Division Two]] side [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] to gain experience as a first team player, which he saw as a valuable experience.<ref name="findarticles"/> He spent a month with Swindon, scoring two goals in six games. On the international scene, Milner continued to develop, representing the England Under-20 team at the [[2003 FIFA World Youth Championship|2003 World Youth Championship]]. Not long after, [[Peter Taylor]] called him up to the [[England national under-21 football team|England under-21 side]], for which he débuted  against [[Sweden national under-21 football team|Sweden]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Chopra earns U21s draw | author=Gerry Cox | url=http://www.thefa.com/England/U21s/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2004/03/SwedenU21vEnglandU21_MR.htm | accessdate=June 20 | accessyear=2007 }}</ref>

However, Leeds United's fortunes differed, and they struggled to keep their position in the league. Milner believed the experience made him stronger emotionally and taught him how to deal with team problems.<ref name="findarticles"/> Leeds's [[promotion and relegation|relegation]] to the [[Football League Championship|Championship]] led to speculation over Milner's future at the club, although he had signed a five-year deal with Leeds the previous year. [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] and [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] all expressed an interest in him,<ref name="ESPN">{{cite web
  | title = 16 James Milner | Midfielder
  | publisher = [[ESPN]]
  | url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/players/profile?id=26843&cc=5739
  | accessdate = 2007-07-28 }}</ref> but Milner rejected Tottenham's offer because they were based too far from his family home.<ref name="findarticles3">{{cite web
  | title = Football: Versatile Milner may be right for the England left
  | publisher = findarticles
  | date = [[2004-07-25]]
  | url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4159/is_20040725/ai_n12757753
  | accessdate = 2007-09-13 }}</ref><ref name="Milner plots Leeds deal
">{{cite web
  | title = Milner plots Leeds deal
  | publisher = BBC
  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/t/tottenham_hotspur/3710803.stm
  | accessdate = 2007-08-23 }}</ref> Leeds also insisted that he would not be sold, the chairman of the team at the time even referring to him as "the future of Leeds".<ref name="findarticles"/> However, financial problems eventually forced them to sell him to [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] after accepting an offer of £3,600,000. The final total paid was £5,000,000 after a certain number of appearances for the new club. Milner was not happy to be leaving the club he had supported as a child, but wished to do what was in the club's best interest.<ref name="findarticles">{{cite web
  | last = Shaw
  | first = Phil
|url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20051231/ai_n15981206 
|title = FOOTBALL THE PREMIERSHIP INTERVIEW: One to watch in 2006: 'Players 
|publisher=findarticles 
|date = [[2005-12-31]]
|accessdate = 2007-07-28}}</ref> In July 2004, Milner agreed a five-year deal with Newcastle.<ref name="ESPN"/>

===Newcastle United===
[[Image:JamesMilner.JPG|right|thumb|120px|Milner warming up prior to a pre-season friendly match.]]
Milner made his first appearance for [[Newcastle United]] during their pre-season tour of Asia, and scored his first goal for the club against [[Kitchee]] in [[Hong Kong]]. The match ended in a 1&ndash;1 draw.<ref name="Impact">{{cite web
  | last = Pearson
  | first = James
  | title = Robson delight at Milner impact
  | publisher = [[Sky Sports]]
  | date = [[2004-07-19]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11678_2305641,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-29 }}</ref> During this tour, he took the opportunity to observe how [[Alan Shearer]] dealt with the fans and press. He said that associating with people like Shearer taught him how to deal with the media.<ref name="Sunday Telegraph"/>

His first Premier League game for Newcastle was a 2&ndash;2 draw against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]], in which he played on the right wing despite having regularly featured on the left for Leeds. After the game he stated that he had no preference where on the pitch he played.<ref name="position">{{cite web
  | last = ORourke
  | first = Peter
  | title = Milner makes Magpies vow
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2004-08-18]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11678_2308355,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}</ref> In September he made his début in European competition, when Newcastle played [[Israel]]'s [[Hapoel Bnei Sakhnin FC|Bnei Sakhnin]] in the [[UEFA Cup]]. In that same month, he scored his first competitive goal for the club in a 3&ndash;1 win against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]].<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Newcastle 3-1 West Brom
  | publisher = BBC
  | date = [[2004-09-25]]
  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/3661816.stm
  | accessdate = 2007-08-23 }}</ref> 

Things changed for Milner after [[Bobby Robson]], who Milner considered his mentor, was sacked and replaced by [[Graeme Souness]]. Despite starting in 13 league games, the midfielder only played his first full Premier League game for Newcastle on [[24 April]] [[2005]]. By the end of the season, he had made 41 appearances in all competitions and scored once. Souness remarked controversially that the club would not win "with a team of James Milners". Milner's response to this was reported as "mature", although he was frustrated at not being used as a starter for most of the season.<ref name="Rooney">{{cite web
  | last = McNALLY
  | first = BRIAN
  | title = Football: ROO TAKES THE HEAT OFF JAMES
  | publisher = findarticles
  | date = [[2005-05-15]]
  | url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4161/is_20050515/ai_n14628658
  | accessdate = 2007-09-19 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last = Buckingham
  | first = Mark
  | title = Milner's Magpies hope
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2005-03-29]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11678_2330925,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-09-10 }}</ref> [[2004-05 in English football|2004&ndash;05]] was also the season in which Milner scored his first goal for the England Under-21 side. This was in a qualification game against [[Wales national under-21 football team|Wales]]  during the [[2007 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship|2007 European Under-21 Championship]]. England won the match 2&ndash;0.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Bradbury
  | first = Jamie
  | title = Milner fires U21s through
  | publisher = [[The FA]]
  | date = [[2006-09-06]]
  | url = http://www.thefa.com/England/U21s/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2006/09/EnglandU21s_vSwitzerland.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-29 }}</ref>

At the start of the [[2005-06 in English football|2005&ndash;06]] season, Milner scored his first European goal. This was in a 3&ndash;1 win away against [[FK ZTS Dubnica]] in the [[Intertoto Cup]],<ref>{{cite web
  | title = ZTS Dubnica 1&ndash;3 Newcastle
  | publisher = BBC
  | date = [[2005-06-17]]
  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/4689063.stm
  | accessdate = 2007-07-29 }}</ref> during which he also set up the third goal for Shearer. Milner's run of form continued when he scored again in the next round against [[Deportivo de La Coruña|Deportivo la Coruña]], but a clause in Newcastle's purchase of [[Nolberto Solano]] from [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] resulted in Milner being loaned to Villa for the rest of the season. Villa manager [[David O'Leary]], who had managed Milner at Leeds, said he believed Villa got the better of the deal,<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Pearson
  | first = James
  | title = O'Leary happy with Nobby deal
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2005-09-01]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11677_2347428,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-29 }}</ref> and that he hoped to improve Milner as a player.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Buckingham
  | first = Mark 
  | title = O'Leary to improve Milner
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2005-09-01]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11677_2347843,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-29 }}</ref>
====Aston Villa====
Milner made his Villa début on [[12 September]] in a Premiership match against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]], and scored his first goal for the club in a 1&ndash;1 draw against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] on [[17 September]]. He then helped his side recover from being 3&ndash;1 down at half-time against [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]] in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]], scoring two goals to help the side to an 8&ndash;3 win. Although Villa made a poor start to the season, Milner remained confident that they would recover after a break for international duty, praising the quality of the squad and the team's spirit.<ref name="team">{{cite web
  | last = Buckingham
  | first = Mark 
  | title = Milner upbeat for Villa
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2005-10-04]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11677_2350606,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-29 }}</ref>
 
O'Leary confirmed many times during the season that he would like to sign Milner permanently but doubted he would be given the opportunity.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Livie
  | first = Alex
  | title = O'Leary expects to lose Milner
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2005-11-24]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11677_2355212,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref> He even pulled out of signing [[Robert Huth]] so that he would have the funds to sign Milner permanently if the opportunity arose.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Buckingham
  | first = Mark
  | title = Villa out of Huth chase
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2005-12-23]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11668_2358958,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref> Milner himself said he would like to join Villa because of the probability of being a regular starter, but admitted that his future was beyond his control.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Buckingham
  | first = Mark
  | title = Milner waits on future
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2005-12-24]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11677_2358774,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref> Milner was generally seen as a positive signing in what was a disappointing season for Villa.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Rutledge
  | first = Lewis
  | title = O'Leary joy at Milner return
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2006-04-14]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11677_2373489,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref>

Negotiations between Villa and Newcastle began in May 2006 regarding Villa's desire to sign Milner permanently. Newly appointed Newcastle manager [[Glenn Roeder]] appeared to have more appreciation for Milner's ability than Souness had shown, and expressed his desire to keep him at Newcastle. With a lack of transfer funds at Villa, in addition to a change of management at the club, a deal appeared unlikely. In June, Villa rejected an offer of Milner as part of a trade for [[Gareth Barry]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Jackson
  | first = Phil
  | title = Villa no to Barry-Milner swap
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2006-06-14]]
  | url = http://home.skysports.com/list.aspx?hlid=394951&plid=15157&clid=7&cpid=8
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref> It was rumoured in July that [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]] had agreed to sign him for £3,500,000.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Saturday's gossip column 
  | publisher = BBC
  | date = [[2006-07-22]]
  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/gossip_and_transfers/5205424.stm
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref> However, when Villa were taken over by American billionaire [[Randy Lerner]], and [[Martin O'Neill]] appointed as new manager, the previous deal was resurrected. Villa made an improved offer to Newcastle on [[30 August]], which was accepted by Newcastle chairman [[Freddy Shepherd]]. Media sources quoted the transfer fee as being £4,000,000. However at the last moment, Newcastle recalled Milner and the talks broke down.<ref name="Roeder">{{cite web
  | last = Buckingham
  | first = Mark  
  | title = Roeder backs Milner stance
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2006-08-31]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11677_2388251,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-11 }}</ref>

====Return to Newcastle United====
[[Image:James Milner 17.jpg|150px|thumb|left|Milner takes a free kick during the [[2006-07 in English football|2006–07 season]].]]
Newcastle's players and manager [[Glenn Roeder]] reacted positively to the recall at the start of the [[2006-07 in English football|2006&ndash;07]] season.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Sol hails return of young gun Milner
  | publisher = officialplayersites
  | date = [[2006-07-14]]
  | url = http://www.officialplayersites.com/players/solano/article.php?id=815
  | accessdate = 2007-08-13 }}</ref> Roeder was criticised for the way he had handled the negotiations with Villa, but refused to apologise. He also highly praised Milner's ability, the way he had handled the Villa transfer fiasco, and confirmed he would play him in "plenty of games".<ref name="Roeder"/> This proved to be the case, as Milner started the season playing regularly in the first team and remained a starter for the entire season. He also continued to impress at international level, helping the England Under-21 side to reach the playoffs of the [[2007 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship|Under-21 European Championship]] qualifiers. He scored the winning goal of a 3&ndash;2 win over [[Switzerland national under-21 football team|Switzerland]], securing England a place in the playoffs. Newcastle made a poor start to the season in the Premier League, but Milner played a key role in helping them advance through the group stage of the [[UEFA Cup 2006-07|UEFA Cup]]. Rumours began to spread in December 2006 that he would be sold during the [[transfer window]], although these were dismissed by Milner and Roeder.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = ORourke
  | first = Peter
  | title = Milner expects Toon stay
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2006-12-04]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11677_2396713,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref> 

His first goal of the season, a shot from 25 yards in Newcastle's 2&ndash;2 draw with [[Manchester United]] on [[1 January]] [[2007]], was described as "stunning".<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Chowdhury
  | first = Saj
  | title =  Newcastle 2-2 Man Utd
  | publisher = BBC
  | date = [[2007-01-01]]
  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6205747.stm
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref> He scored two more goals in the next three weeks, against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] and then against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]. Both of these were also scored from at least 20&nbsp;yards away from goal. Milner signed a new contract at Newcastle on [[January 20]], which secured his future at the club until 2011.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Scurr
  | first = Andrew  
  | title = Roeder Rejects Milner Exit Talk
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2006-12-30]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11678_2398870,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-11 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last = Higham
  | first = Paul
  | title = Toon see-off Villa challenge
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2007-01-31]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/football/match_report/0,19764,11065_0,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref>

Roeder praised his progress during the season and stated that he believed Milner to be the hardest training player at the club. During the 2006&ndash;07 season, Milner displayed his ability to play comfortably on either wing, scoring and setting up goals with both feet on either flank.<ref name="Lampard">{{cite web
  | last = Hackett
  | first = Robin
  | title = Roeder hails dynamic Milner
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2007-04-24]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11678_2412065,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref> In June, Milner competed for England at the [[European Under-21 Football Championship]] where he played in all four of England's matches. He was booked in the semi-final against [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|the Netherlands]], which meant he would have missed the final. He did, however, score twice in the penalty shootout, which England lost 13&ndash;12.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Wilson
  | first =  Jeremy
  | title = England go out after 32-penalty shoot-out drama
  | publisher = The Guardian  
  | date = [[2007-06-21]]
  | url = http://football.guardian.co.uk/News_Story/0,,2107676,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-23 }}</ref> In May 2007 [[Sam Allardyce]] took over as manager of Newcastle and signed Milner to a four-year contract.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Milner deal may be Sam’s best move
  | publisher = icnewcastle
  | date = [[2007-06-14]]
  | url = http://icnewcastle.icnetwork.co.uk/0200sport/0100football/tm_headline=milner-deal-may-be-sam-8217-s-best-move%26method=full%26objectid=19453436%26siteid=50081-name_page.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref> Milner confirmed that he was happy about his future at the club and with the new manager.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Milner is Sam happy player
  | publisher = icnewcastle
  | date = [[2007-08-17]]
  | url = http://icnewcastle.icnetwork.co.uk/newcastleunited/chroniclesport/tm_headline=milner-is-sam-happy-player&method=full&objectid=19650900&siteid=50081-name_page.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref>

It was rumoured that Milner would make his full England début in a friendly against [[Germany national football team|Germany]], but in the end he was left out of the squad.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Taylor And Milner To Be Part Of 'Huge Squad'?
  | publisher = astonvilla-mad
  | date = [[2007-08-17]]
  | url = http://www.astonvilla-mad.co.uk/news/loadgnrl.asp?id=348618&teamno=386
  | accessdate = 2007-08-17 }}</ref> He was, however, included in the Under-21 squad for a friendly against [[Romania national under-21 football team|Romania]] which ended in a 1&ndash;1 draw.<ref>{{cite web
  | title =  England U21 v Romania U21
  | publisher = BBC
  | date = [[2007-08-21]]
  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/6956354.stm
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}</ref> A month later he set an under-21 record by making his 30th appearance for the side in a 3&ndash;0 against [[Montenegro national under-21 football team|Montenegro]]. He set up the first goal of this game with a corner.<ref>{{cite web
  | title =  England's Youngsters Show The Way
  | publisher = goal
  | date = [[2007-09-07]]
  | url = http://goal.com/en/Articolo.aspx?ContenutoId=407351
  | accessdate = 2007-09-09}}</ref> Historically, players with several England Under-21 appearances have not progressed to become regulars in the senior side, so some have doubted whether he would be able to successfully make the transition.<ref>{{cite web
  | title =  International - Milner battles Under-21 curse
  | publisher = Eurosport
  | date = [[2007-08-21]]
  | url = http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/21082007/58/international-milner-battles-under-21-curse.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}</ref>

==Style of play==
Milner has a positive, unselfish approach to football and his teammates, and plays with a fair amount of pace.<ref name="TheFA">{{cite web
|url = http://www.thefa.com/England/SeniorTeam/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/06/TakeYourPick_28June05.htm
|title = Take your pick
|publisher= the fa
|date = [[2005-06-28]]
|accessdate = 2007-09-12}}</ref><ref name="findarticles2"/><ref name="team"/> Because of this, his main role on the team is as a wide midfielder who creates scoring opportunities as well as taking the ball past defenders. He therefore does not score many goals, but does produce several [[assist (football)|assists]]. Former teammate [[Nolberto Solano]] said that because of his pace, Milner would become an important team player.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Sol hails return of young gun Milner
  | publisher = officialplayersites
  | url = http://www.officialplayersites.com/players/solano/article.php?id=815
  | date = [[2006-07-14]]
  | accessdate = 2007-07-29 }}</ref>

He has the ability to pass and shoot with both feet, but describes defending as one of his weaknesses.<ref name="interview">{{cite web
  | title = The boy's a bit special - James Milner
  | publisher = fourfourtwo
  | url = http://www.fourfourtwo.premiumtv.co.uk/page/TheBoys/0,,11442~607366,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-29 }}</ref> He therefore usually goes forward for [[Set piece (football)|set pieces]] and is often a candidate to take [[Corner kick|corners]] and [[Direct free kick|free kicks]]<ref name="everything2">{{cite web
|url = http://www.everything2.com/index.pl?node_id=1409685
|title = James Milner
|publisher= everything2
|date = [[2003-01-02]]
|accessdate = 2007-09-12}}</ref> — this is supported by his ability to produce accurate [[Cross (football)|crosses]] and play on either side of the field.<ref>{{cite web
| last = Gilder
| first = Paul
| url= http://icnewcastle.icnetwork.co.uk/newcastleunited/fixtures/tm_objectid=18037804&method=full&siteid=50081&headline=-name_page.html
| title=Palermo 0, Newcastle United 1
| publisher=icnetwork
| date=[[2006-11-03]]
| accessdate=2007-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
| url= http://www.goal.com/en-US/Articolo.aspx?ContenutoId=175231
| title=Uefa Group H Report: Magpies Make More Cup Magic
| publisher=goal
| date=[[2006-11-24]]
| accessdate=2007-09-13}}</ref> Despite these positive qualities, some commentators still criticise his crossing ability as sub-par.<ref>{{cite web
| url= http://archive.thenorthernecho.co.uk/2004/12/28/27998.html
| title=We deserve all this flak, admits Given
| publisher=the northern echo
| date=[[2004-12-28]]
| accessdate=2007-09-13}}</ref>
{{Quote_box|
 width=30%
|align=left
|quote=All my life I've wanted to do what I'm doing now. Now I'm here, and enjoying every minute of it. You've got to make a few sacrifices, but I don't mind that.
|source=&ndash;James Milner<ref name="findarticles2"/>
|}}

He has been described as being "a good reader of the game",<ref name="nufc">{{cite web
  | title =  Profile
  | publisher = [[Newcastle United]] official site
  | url = http://www.nufc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Profiles/0,,10278~23079,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-29 }}</ref> and his awareness of players around him, as well as his willingness to pass, has been described as mature for a player of his age.<ref name="Chelsea"/> It also allows him to pick out a forward run being made by a teammate from a range of positions on the field. This awareness has also given him the confidence to take on defenders.<ref name="everything2"/>

Milner believes that he is a hard-worker, confident and relaxed,<ref name="interview"/> expressing willingness to play as much as possible.<ref>{{cite web
|url = http://icnewcastle.icnetwork.co.uk/newcastleunited/journalsport/tm_method=full%26objectid=19609527%26siteid=50081-name_page.html
|title = FOOTBALL THE PREMIERSHIP INTERVIEW: One to watch in 2006: 'Players 
|publisher= icnetwork
|date = [[2007-08-11]]
|accessdate = 2007-08-13}}</ref> His good work ethic in training has been compared to that of [[Frank Lampard|Frank Lampard]].<ref name="Lampard"/> Milner also feels that [[Wayne Rooney]]'s move to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and success as a player has taken a lot of pressure off his own career — commenting that "I have been able to concentrate on football and ignore everything else".<ref name="Rooney"/>
During his career, Milner has been [[Misconduct (football)|booked]] 15 times and has never been sent off.<ref name="stats"/><ref name="footballanorak">{{cite web
  | title = James Milner News and Statistics
  | publisher = footballanorak
  | url = http://www.footballanorak.com/James-Milner-pid-670.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-31 }}</ref>

SkySports.com gave him an overall player rating of 6.6 out of 10.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = James Milner
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/football/player/0,,11678_247364,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-11 }}</ref>

